CC.rulesIndex = [{"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 1, "t": "Far below the Catacombs lies a deeper domain ﬁ lled with untold riches… and immense danger! Test your fate in the fabled Underworld. Unique items tempt you in underworld markets, and mysterious Fate cards offer new ways to enhance your score. Discover mystical towers to increase your speed, reshape your deck at an underground lake, or recruit an Imp Assistant to learn even more from your Secret Tomes. Screeching harpies hoard precious undercoins, and the Underworld Guardian offers special riches to those who survive the encounter! Glory awaits for the boldest thieves. Pay the toll or meet your doom in CLANK! Catacombs: Underworld!"}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 2, "t": "Components 2 The dungeon cards from this expansion can be identiﬁ ed by this watermark in the game text box. New tiles have the same mark on one corner of the front of the tile, to help you during Setup. You may also use these marks to sort and remove the components when you wish to play without this expansion (or to remove them while you play, as they're revealed). u during arks to sort en you wish r to remove 50 Dungeon Deck cards 22 Fate Deck cards 6 Depths Tiles Underworld Starting Tile 7 Underworld Tiles Haunted Tiles and Ghosts There are new haunted tiles in this expansion (both Depths and Underworld tiles). These work just like the haunted tiles in CLANK! Catacombs (including with a card like Spectral Rider). However, there are still only ﬁ ve white Ghost cubes in the game. If all ﬁ ve have already been taken from the Bank when you discover a haunted tile, you don't have to add another Ghost. Consider yourself… lucky?"}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 3, "t": "3 4 Reference cards Magic Lyre 16-point artifact 6 Major Secrets 6 Minor Secrets 3 Artifact Enhancers 4 Prisoners Market Board 8 Harpy tokens 6 Market Items Undercoins 20 worth 1; 2 worth 5 These are not meant to be limited; if you run out and need more, make any convenient substitution. Underworld Guardian marker and Monster card Monkey Shrine replacement Enhance your experience with the Dire Wolf Game Room companion app for your PC, smartphone, or tablet. 5 Ladder tokens 3 Imp Assistants"}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 4, "t": "Setup 1 Prepare your stack of square tiles as follows: First, shufﬂ e the six Depths tiles from Underworld. (Do not add them to your existing tiles yet!) Return three to the game box without looking at them; you will not use them in this game. Next, separately shufﬂ e your existing Depths tiles. Take the top seven without looking at them, then shufﬂ e into those the three Underworld tiles you kept. Place this shufﬂ ed stack of 10 tiles on top of the remaining Depths tiles. Finally, when you shufﬂ e the \"safe\" tiles, place only three (not four) on top of the assembled stack of Depths tiles. (When playing this expansion, you'll explore only three tiles before reaching the Depths.) Shufﬂ e the seven regular Underworld tiles and place them in a face-down stack next to the square tiles. 4 1 2 Scan here to learn how to play the game by watching a video. 2 When stocking the Bank: Add the undercoins, and the harpy and ladder tokens. tokens. Shufﬂ e the Underworld major secrets, minor secrets, and prisoners with the existing tokens of the same types. Use the Underworld Market Board instead of the one from Catacombs. Place all market items on the board, in two separate rows. The new River Lamp goes on the top row with all previously existing market items. The other ﬁ ve new market items (Underworld market items) go in the bottom row. When playing with CLANK! Catacombs: Underworld, these steps modify and add to the setup of the original game."}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 5, "t": "3 Place the Underworld starting tile in your playing space, with room separating it from the Catacombs starting tile. You may place either side face up; however, for your ﬁ rst game, it is recommended that you use the \"front\" side (pictured at the right). Place these tokens in the various marked rooms on the tile: The magic lyre (16-point artifact). The three artifact enhancers, stacked with the 2x token on top, along with the Underworld Guardian marker. The three Imp Assistants, stacked with the 4-value token on top. One harpy token (taken from the Bank). When using the front side of the Underworld starting tile, take one random Prisoner token from the Bank and put it face up in the marked room. (It is not yet freed, so do not carry out any of its \"immediate\" effects.) If you use the back side of the tile, the Monkey Shrine room moves from the Catacombs starting tile to the Underworld. Place the three Monkey Idols on the Monkey Shrine room there. Then use the Monkey Shrine replacement token (with either side face up) to cover the Monkey Shrine room on the Catacombs starting tile. (When playing the front side of the Underworld starting tile, you don't need the Monkey Shrine replacement token; return it to the game box.) 4 Place the Underworld Guardian card in the Reserve, next to the Goblin. Shufﬂ e the 50 Underworld Dungeon Deck cards into the Dungeon Deck, before dealing cards to form the Dungeon Row as usual. Shufﬂ e the fate deck and place it near the Dungeon Deck. 5 4 5 Give each player a reference card to keep in their supply. For your ﬁ rst game, it's recommended that each player take one undercoin from the Bank (making it a little easier to descend to the Underworld). 3"}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 6, "t": "The Underworld The Underworld is a separate area of the dungeon. Its tiles aren't directly adjacent to any regular CLANK! Catacombs tile; players must ﬁ nd a special method to descend to the Underworld. The Underworld consists of a maximum of six tiles. One is the Underworld starting tile, which has ﬁ ve edges labeled with the letters A through E. Those letters correspond to ﬁ ve other Underworld tiles which can be discovered during the game and placed directly adjacent to the Underworld starting tile. When you need to move onto an undiscovered Underworld tile, reveal the next one from the top of the face-down stack in the Bank and place it where you are moving to. You do not choose an orientation; it must be placed with the shorter ﬂ at edge touching the Underworld starting tile. Because of their different shapes (and magic beyond mortal comprehension), the six Underworld tiles can never be rotated by any means. The Underworld is far away and dangerous. If you are knocked out there, you score 0 points. The Underworld is not the Depths. (It's even deeper!) Cards that do things in the Depths (such as the fate card Death, or The Warden from CLANK! Catacombs) do not work in the Underworld. All That Glitters Is Not Gold The Underworld has its own currency, the undercoin. In all ways, it works just like a regular gold coin: you can spend it to buy market items, each one is worth 1 point at the end of the game, and so on. When spending gold, you may spend undercoins instead, or a mix of both. When you play Underworld Dealer, you may either gain 1 undercoin or spend 3 gold to acquire a Secret Tome. If you choose the Secret Tome, you may spend undercoins as some or all of the cost, because they have the same value as gold. There are rooms where you can earn undercoins, just like previously existing rooms that reward you with gold. When you enter such a room, take the amount shown from the Bank (but only once for each room during each turn). The Underworld Takes a Toll Beyond their gold value, undercoins are used to pay some mildly unpleasant \"tolls\" you'll face while in the Underworld. Whenever you start your turn in the Underworld, you must immediately pay a toll of 1 undercoin to the Bank. If you cannot pay this toll, you must make +2 Clank! instead. (You cannot choose to make the Clank! if you have an undercoin to pay the toll.) The servants of the Underworld do not take kindly to freeloaders, so if you want to visit the Underworld, you may ﬁ rst want to get your hands on an undercoin or two. In addition, some tunnels in the Underworld are marked with toll booths. To move through such a tunnel, you must pay 1 undercoin to the Bank. (You may not make Clank! instead.) As with other icons on tunnels, when you use a teleport to move through a toll booth icon, you ignore it. 6 Marble Guardian When you defeat this monster from CLANK! Catacombs, if you are in the Underworld, you place a new Underworld tile in an available space next to your current tile."}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 7, "t": "7 How Do I Get There? The main way to reach the Underworld is by using a ladder on one of the new Depths tiles. If you are in a ladder room, you may spend one Boot to descend into the Underworld. Each ladder is labeled with a letter, A through E. When you use one of them, you arrive in the ladder room of the corresponding Underworld tile. If that Underworld tile hasn't been placed yet, then you discover a tile to place there. If something allows you to teleport to an adjacent room, you may teleport down the ladder instead. You may spend one Boot (or a teleport) to return from a ladder room in the Underworld to the corresponding room in the Depths - but only if the ladder room with the matching letter actually exists there! During setup, you exclude some of the CLANK! Catacombs: Underworld Depths tiles (thus excluding some letters from the game). Even the Depths tiles you have included may not have been discovered yet. To help you identify paths out of the Underworld, use the ladder tokens from the Bank to mark the Underworld ladder rooms that have a connection in the Depths. The yellow player, Brooke, has been moving through the Underworld for a while and is now in ladder room B. There is no ladder room B in the Depths, so she can't use that ladder. She must move to a different Underworld tile with a ladder room that has a corresponding room in the Depths. The red player, Eddie, is in the Depths in ladder room A. He may spend a Boot to move to ladder room A in the Underworld (and from that room, could spend one Boot to move back). An underworld chute has no letter. When you descend one, you may enter any ladder room on an Underworld tile (even one that hasn't been discovered yet, if you choose). However, an underworld chute is a one-way trip: down! You can't use an underworld chute to ascend from the Underworld to the Depths, not even by teleporting. The green player, Corbin, ﬁ nds this tile in the Depths. He could spend a Boot to descend, arriving on any of the ﬁ ve ladder rooms that can exist in the Underworld. Three Underworld tiles have not yet been discovered, so if Corbin chooses ladder room C, D, or E, he would reveal a new tile. If he chooses to move to ladder room B, he'll arrive in the same room as Brooke (above), and like her will not be able to move directly back to the Depths. If he chooses to move to ladder room A, he could leave the Underworld by moving to the Depths tile that Eddie began on. The Underworld starting tile features a special return portal. This works like the regular portals of CLANK! Catacombs except for one key difference: it is a one-way portal. You may only use it to leave the Underworld, exiting to any other portal. You cannot enter the Underworld using this portal. From Trash to Treasure Some cards in this expansion provide you with something \"when you trash this.\" You can't just trash these cards whenever you choose; you must ﬁ nd some other means to do so. Brooke enters an underground lake room (described on page 9). She chooses to trash Escape Plan from her discard pile. She gains two Boots, and doesn't have to stop in Crystal Caves for the rest of her turn. hs. move to ladder room"}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 8, "t": "Underworld Features The Underworld Guardian The powerful Kerberos - or Kerbie, for short - vigilantly stands guard in the darkness, protecting important items while hungering for his next meal. When you enter the room with the Underworld Guardian, you must immediately ﬁ ght him (using 3 swords) or take 2 damage. When you defeat him, you receive two beneﬁ ts. First, you take the 2x artifact enhancer from the room. Second, you take the Underworld Guardian as a trophy, placing him in your personal supply; there he counts as a \"bonus artifact.\" (Increase the rage when you take him, but he does not count against your artifact limit.) Because the Underworld Guardian appears in every game using CLANK! Catacombs: Underworld, a card is included to place in the reserve as a reference for the above rules. You do not take additional damage if you remain in the room with the Underworld Guardian, but you may choose to ﬁ ght him on the same turn or a later one (even if you did not ﬁ ght him when you ﬁ rst entered). Remember that you can't voluntarily take damage if you have no cubes in your supply, or if doing so would completely ﬁ ll your Health Meter. In these situations, you can't enter the Guardian's room. Artifact Enhancers The player who defeats the Underworld Guardian takes the 2x artifact enhancer. Later, up to two other players may enter the room, each taking one of the other artifact enhancers. (No player may have more than one.) At the end of the game, an artifact enhancer is a multiplier on the value of the best artifact you have (rounding up if necessary). Brooke defeats the Underworld Guardian and takes the 2x artifact enhancer. Later, Corbin enters the room and takes one of the 1.5x artifact enhancers. At the end of the game, Brooke's best artifact is worth 16 points, which her artifact enhancer increases to 32. Corbin's best artifact is worth 15 points, which his enhancer increases to 23 points. When using artifact value to break a tie score, it is possible (though unlikely) that artifact enhancers could cause two players to have an artifact of the same value. In this case, the artifact with the higher unmodiﬁ ed value wins the tie. Magic Lyre This special 16-point artifact can be found in the Underworld. The chains in the room secure the Lyre so that it can only be removed by a player in its room. Lairs and Lost Chambers has several cards (such as Artifact Detector) with ARRIVE text that returns an artifact to the artifact stack. These can never affect the Magic Lyre. The same expansion includes Lost Chambers that allow a player to take an artifact from elsewhere in the dungeon. They can't be used on the Magic Lyre. Imp Assistants Deep in the Underworld is the Forbidden Library, a fabled place where ancient and peculiar knowledge is kept. Even more peculiar are the keepers, the Imp Assistants. When you ﬁ rst enter the room with the Imp Assistants, you must take the top one from the stack. Each player may have only one Imp Assistant. Once you have an Imp Assistant, for the rest of the game, each time you acquire a Secret Tome, you must immediately remove two cards of your choice from the Dungeon Row. (Place them in the Dungeon discard pile; you are not \"trashing\" them). This effect also applies whenever you acquire any card that says it \"counts as a Secret Tome.\" At the end of the game, you score points for the Imp Assistant: the number shown for each Secret Tome you have. At the end of the game, Brooke has the Imp Assistant pictured above, as well as two Secret Tomes, the Book of the Dead major secret, and the Tome of Intellect. She scores 16 points for the Imp Assistant. 8 )"}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 9, "t": "9 Fate Rooms Fate rooms are marked with the same symbol found on the backs of the fate cards. The ﬁ rst time you enter any fate room, draw three cards from the fate deck. Choose one to keep, then return the other two to the bottom of the fate deck. You may have only one fate card per game (though the Gauntlets of Destiny market item allows you to have one more). Each fate card is unique, with the potential to affect your score and other possible beneﬁ ts. You may look at your own fate card at any time; otherwise, unless it speciﬁ es a time to reveal it, keep it hidden until the end of the game. Temperance and the Fool are examples of fate cards you keep hidden until the end of the game, when you total your score. Temperance is worth 4 points. The Fool is worth 10 points if you have two Stumble cards in your deck (or 0, if you don't). Judgement speciﬁ es that you should reveal it immediately when you take it. The dragon then attacks. Later, at the end of the game, it is worth 5 points. Underworld Markets The ﬁ ve new Underworld market items in this expansion can be bought only while you're in a market room in the Underworld. These are the only items available in an Underworld market room; you cannot buy a regular market item there. Cards that allow you to acquire market items in alternative ways (such as Golden Flute and Ogre Merchant, from CLANK! Catacombs) depend on your current location. While you're in the Underworld, they allow you to take only Underworld market items; when you're not, they allow you to take only regular market items. Underworld Prison On the front side of the Underworld starting tile, one room holds a Prisoner (placed during Setup). The ﬁ rst player to enter this room frees this prisoner immediately, without needing to spend a Lockpick. Other Tile Features Harpies Harpies are dangerous birdlike spirits that infest the Underworld, though some have started migrating to the Catacombs! When you discover a new tile with a harpy room, take a harpy token from the Bank and place it in that room. When you enter a room with a harpy token, you must immediately ﬁ ght it (using 2 swords) or take 1 damage. When you defeat a harpy token, you receive two beneﬁ ts. First, take it as a trophy, placing it in your personal supply. Second, take one undercoin from the Bank for each harpy trophy you have (including the one you just defeated). You do not take additional damage if you remain in a room with a harpy token, but you may choose to ﬁ ght it on the same turn or a later one (even if you did not ﬁ ght the harpy when you ﬁ rst entered). Remember that you can't voluntarily take damage if you have no cubes in your supply, or if doing so would completely ﬁ ll your Health Meter. In these situations, you can't enter a harpy token's room. One card, the Harpy Matriarch, also counts as a harpy trophy. Though it gives you exactly two undercoins when you defeat it (no matter how many other harpy trophies you have), it is counted as a harpy by harpy tokens you defeat in the future. It is also worth points at the end of the game, as described on the card. Underground Lakes When you enter an underground lake room, you may immediately trash a card in your play area or discard pile. As with other rewards you receive from entering a room, you may do this only once each turn per underground lake room. Towers When you start your turn in a tower room, you get a Boot. Some new features in CLANK! Catacombs: Underworld aren't only found in the Underworld. k t it 5 i"}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 10, "t": "Variants You may choose to use either or both of these variant rules for your game. Fixed Dimensions Because of the extra space the Underworld takes, you might consider this variant if you have limited table space. At the start of the game, players agree to limit the layout of square tiles in the dungeon - to a grid that's \"5 by 5,\" \"or \"6 by 6.\" During the game, no player can place a square tile in a position that would exceed the limit. In a 5 by 5 game, Brooke is leaving the lower left room on her tile. She cannot go south because the dungeon is already 5 tiles tall, so she heads west. The new tile she discovers has a tunnel on two corners that would continue Brooke's movement to the south. She can't place the tile in a way that would cause this, so she must place it in a different orientation instead - entering either the market or the wayshrine. (If she had 9 damage and no swords available to defeat the tunnel monster before the wayshrine, she would have to choose the market room. In an extreme case with a different tile - where the ﬁ xed dimensions restrict orientation, and all legal orientations lead to \"lethal damage\" - a player must accept that outcome.) Mercy You may play this variant with or without CLANK! Catacombs: Underworld, though it is strongly recommended when you are using the Fixed Dimensions variant above. During your turn, you may invoke Mercy if you ﬁ nd yourself trapped: if there's no room adjacent to yours, and no way to place a new tile to escape. In this situation, you may rotate your current tile to any orientation so that you are no longer stuck. Corbin ended his last turn on a Wayshrine. Then a Grave Robber arrived on the Dungeon Row, rotating his tile 180 degrees. The 5 by 5 limit of his game means it's impossible to move east from the Wayshrine, so Corbin is trapped. He invokes Mercy on his next turn, rotating his tile so he has a path to leave. X Combining with Lairs and Lost Chambers You may combine this expansion with CLANK! Catacombs: Lairs and Lost Chambers. Treat the Underworld Guardian marker and reference card together as a single trophy. The harpies (both the tokens, and the Harpy Matriarch) are also trophies. All of these are used like other trophies in Lairs and Lost Chambers. Each fate room is a lost chamber (as marked by their golden walls), and thus is affected by cards like Silver Arch and Swap Meet. The Underworld Guardian's room, however, is not a lair. (Antimagic properties there prevent the Silver Arch from taking you there.) 10"}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 11, "t": "Credits 11 Game Design Paul Dennen Additional Game Design Phil Amylon, Corey Burkhart, Andy Clautice, Evan Lorentz, Nation Morath, Kevin Spak, Caleb Vance, Luke Wyman Executive Producer Scott Martins Art Direction Clay Brooks, Nate Storm Art and Graphic Design Anika Burrell, Leah Falin, Julianne Stone Card Illustration Derek Herring, Kenan Jackson, Raul Ramos, Nate Storm Production Evan Lorentz Special thanks to: All of the awesome Dire Wolf Digital team members, and their friends and families, who helped to playtest CLANK! Catacombs: Underworld. www.direwolfdigital.com /direwolfdigital @direwolfdigital.bsky.social Published by: Dire Wolf Digital. © 2025 Dire Wolf Digital, Inc. All Rights Reserved. Dire Wolf and the Dire Wolf logo are registered trademarks of Dire Wolf Digital, Inc."}, {"x": "uw", "b": "Underworld Rulebook", "p": 12, "t": "Token Reference Guide Prisoners Faithful Immediately take 1 undercoin from the Bank. Also worth 1 point at the end of the game. Haunted Myrmidon Immediately take a Ghost cube from the Bank and place it in the Clank! area. Each turn that you're in the Underworld at any point (including the turn on which you free this prisoner), you gain 1 Sword. Also worth 1 point at the end of the game. Soul Elixir Immediately advance the Dragon marker one space along the Rage Track. You may use this token one time while in the Underworld to heal 2 damage. It is not a Prisoner for any purpose. (Keep until you use it, then return it to the box.) Major Secrets Book of the Dead Keep this token until the end of the game. At that time, it is worth 5 points, and also becomes a Secret Tome (it counts when scoring an Imp Assistant). Greater Potion of Hope Use during your turn to heal 1 damage (or 2, if you're in the Underworld) and gain 1 Boot. (Keep until you use it, then return it to the box.) Undercoin Cache This token counts as 4 undercoins. You may keep it until the end of the game or spend it normally (getting change from the Bank as needed). Minor Secrets Darkiron Ingot You may use this token one time while buying an Underworld market item to pay 3 less Gold. (Keep until you use it, then return it to the box.) If you don't use it, it is worth 2 points at the end of the game. Potion of Hope Use during your turn to gain 1 sword. If you're in the Underworld, you also gain 1 Boot. (Keep until you use it, then return it to the box.) Underworld Chute You may use this token one time while you're in a room that isn't in the Underworld. (Keep until you use it, then place it in the room where you used it.) It becomes an underworld chute that any player may use to descend to (but not return from) the Underworld. If you don't use it, it is worth 1 point at the end of the game. Market Item No regular market item can be bought from a market room in the Underworld. River Lamp When you buy this, immediately take three undercoins from the Bank. (Also worth 5 points at the end of the game.) Underworld Market Items These can only be bought from a market room in the Underworld. Blood Amulet This item is the same as the Blood Amulet in CLANK! Catacombs (though it can only be bought in the Underworld). You must have at least 5 damage to buy it. When you buy it, immediately heal 2 damage. (Also worth 7 points at the end of the game.) Boots of the Wind Each turn (including the turn in which you buy this item), you gain 1 Boot. (Also worth 1 point at the end of the game.) Gauntlets of Destiny When you buy this, immediately draw three cards from the fate deck. Choose one to keep, then return the other two to the bottom of the fate deck. Your fate card limit is increased to two. (Also worth 6 points at the end of the game.) Jester's Cap At the end of the game, this is worth 7 points for each Stumble card you have. It also counts as a crown. Corbin has the Jester's Cap. He scores 6 points for The Empress fate card at the end of the game, because the Cap counts as a crown. River Boat For the rest of the game, every time you trash a card, stack it under this item. When counting your score at the end of the game, count those cards as if they were part of your deck (for their own points and any other effects). In addition, River Boat is worth 8 points, plus an additional point for every card in its stack. After buying the River Boat, Eddie begins stacking each card he trashes under it. By the end of the game, he has a Secret Tome and two Stumbles there. The River Boat is worth 11 points (8, plus 3 for the cards under it). Then those cards are treated as though they're still part of his deck. The Secret Tome is itself worth 7 points, and his Imp Assistant gives him another 4 points for it. Lastly, he has the Fool fate card, which gives him 10 points for having two Stumbles."}, {"x": "lairs", "b": "Lairs & Lost Chambers Rulebook", "p": 1, "t": "Strange sounds have been heard beneath the catacombs… Brave the lairs of the enigmatic Sphinx, the petrifying Medusa, or the formidable Living Statues. Discover lost chambers, each with a unique power found nowhere else in the dungeon. Collect trophies of your adventures to help your legend grow! New mysteries and dangers await in CLANK! Catacombs: Lairs and Lost Chambers!"}, {"x": "lairs", "b": "Lairs & Lost Chambers Rulebook", "p": 2, "t": "Credits Game Design Paul Dennen Additional Game Design and Development Phil Amylon, Andy Clautice, Justin Cohen, Evan Lorentz, Kevin Spak, Jay Treat, Caleb Vance Executive Producer Scott Martins Art Direction Clay Brooks, Derek Herring, Nate Storm Graphic Design Anika Burrell, Julianne Stone Cover Illustration Raul Ramos Card Illustration Allan Santos da Silva, Bruno de Mello, Ernst Eskelsen, Rastislav Le, João Mileski Production Evan Lorentz Special thanks to: The \"weekend warriors\": Robert Cranshaw, Ken Dennen, Doug Dyer, Brian Koziol All of the awesome Dire Wolf Digital team members, and their friends and families, who helped to playtest CLANK! www.direwolfdigital.com /direwolfdigital @direwolfdigital Published by: Dire Wolf Digital. © 2024 Dire Wolf Digital, Inc. All Rights Reserved. Dire Wolf and the Dire Wolf logo are registered trademarks of Dire Wolf Digital, Inc. 2"}, {"x": "lairs", "b": "Lairs & Lost Chambers Rulebook", "p": 3, "t": "50 Dungeon Deck cards The cards from this expansion can be identiﬁ ed by this watermark in the game text box. New tiles have the same mark on one corner of the front of the tile. You may use these marks to sort and remove the components when you wish to play without this expansion (or to remove them while you play, as they're revealed). Components 12 Square Tiles 10 in the Depths 2 in safety 5 Monster Markers 3 Living Statues 1 Medusa 1 Sphinx 3 se marks nts when pansion ay,"}, {"x": "lairs", "b": "Lairs & Lost Chambers Rulebook", "p": 4, "t": "Shufﬂ e the 12 new square tiles with your existing CLANK! Catacombs tiles, according to their two different backs. You will use all Depths tiles in each game, but you still place only four of the \"safe\" tiles (selected at random) on top of the shufﬂ ed stack of Depths tiles. (This means you will return additional \"safe\" tiles to the box without looking them.) Place the ﬁ ve monster markers in the Bank: three Living Statues, one Medusa, and one Sphinx. Shufﬂ e the 50 new cards into the Dungeon Deck, before dealing cards to form the Dungeon Row as usual. Setup is otherwise the same as with CLANK! Catacombs. Setup Trophies In CLANK! Catacombs: Lairs and Lost Chambers, you are able to collect monster markers and some cards as \"trophies.\" When you Fight a Monster or Use a Device that has TROPHY text, take that card and put it face up in your personal supply. (It is not in your play area, and you will never place it in your discard pile.) The TROPHY text applies to you as long as it remains there. When you use 3 swords to defeat Hoard Keeper, you gain and make +1 Clank! for its DEFEAT text. Then, because it has TROPHY text, you put the card face up in your personal supply. At the end of the game, Hoard Keeper is worth for every you have. The ﬁ ve monster markers in this expansion are also collected as trophies when you defeat them. See the Lairs section on the back cover for more details. Although some Devices in this set have only TROPHY text (and not the usual USE text), you are still \"using\" them when you take them as a trophy. The Tinkerer says that \"Each device you use this turn costs less.\" This applies to Cave Bat Wings, even though its text has only the word \"TROPHY\" and not \"USE.\" 4 Enhance your experience with the Dire Wolf Game Room companion app for your PC, smartphone, or tablet. For your ﬁ rst game, you may wish to shufﬂ e the new tiles and cards into the top half of their stacks, to ensure you will see plenty of the new expansion."}, {"x": "lairs", "b": "Lairs & Lost Chambers Rulebook", "p": 5, "t": "New Tile Features Entry Tunnels Some new tiles include \"entry tunnels\" marked in a distinct color. When you discover such a tile during movement, you must place it so that you complete your move onto the tile using one of the entry tunnels. From then on, the entry tunnels have no special meaning. (Players move through them normally, and anything that causes the tile to rotate does so normally.) Pit Traps The ﬁ rst time each turn that you enter a Pit Trap room, you must either: • Fall In: Take 1 damage, and you also cannot spend any more Boots for the rest of the turn. (You can still move using a teleport.) • Evade the Trap: Trash a non-Stumble card from your hand. (Because it must come from your hand, you may ﬁ nd it wise to discover any new tiles during your turn before playing all your cards. Otherwise, you must Fall In.) You may enter more than one Pit Trap room during a single turn; you must Fall In or Evade the Trap once for each room. Remember that you can't voluntarily take damage if you have no cubes in your supply, or if doing so would completely ﬁ ll your Health Meter. In these situations, if you can't Evade the Trap, then you can't voluntarily enter a Pit Trap room. Magic Barriers When a tunnel is marked with a magic barrier, you can't move through it using Boots if you have an artifact. (However, you may teleport through the tunnel even if you do have an artifact.) Linked One-Way Tunnels Some new tiles feature a linked pair of one-way tunnels. When moving through them, the direction you enter from determines which of the two tunnels you use. If you enter this tile from the top edge, you use the tunnel with two Monster icons. If you exit upward from the room at the center of this tile, you use the tunnel without Monster icons, and move onward off the top edge of the tile. If you have the Catacombs Map major secret, you may choose to use either tunnel. 5 Clariﬁ cation on \"Acquire\" Some cards in this set (such as Cavern Prowler, Pack Rat, and Acrobatics) allow you to acquire cards without spending any skill as usually required. Note that these cards cannot be used on monsters (which are defeated, not acquired) or devices (which are used, not acquired)."}, {"x": "lairs", "b": "Lairs & Lost Chambers Rulebook", "p": 6, "t": "Lost Chambers Aegis Shrine If you have a cube in this lost chamber, then when a Ghost would deal damage to you, you may return that cube to your personal supply to prevent that damage. Although you may have only one cube in the Aegis Shrine at a time, if you remove it to prevent damage, you may place a new one by visiting the room again. Altar of the Haunted There is only one space to place a cube in this lost chamber. To do so, you must trash a trophy from your personal supply. You then take 2 Gold from the Bank. You may also take an artifact from any room in the dungeon. (You may still only carry one artifact unless you have a Backpack.) Many new tiles feature either a \"lair\" or \"lost chamber.\" These are unique rooms found nowhere else in the dungeon, and each has its own special rules. Lost chambers are described here, while lairs are described on the back cover of this rulebook. Most lost chambers have one or more spaces where players may place a cube from their personal supply during their turn. Many of the same rules used for Wayshrines in CLANK! Catacombs apply to these lost chambers: you must be in the room to place a cube there, you must place it in an empty space, you cannot mark the same room more than once, and you must have a cube available from your personal supply. Bizarre Bazaar Each of the four spaces in this lost chamber is a unique \"stall\" offering a speciﬁ c \"purchase\" when you place your cube. To do so, you must either spend 3 Gold (returning it to the Bank) or trash a trophy from your personal supply. The four stalls and their offerings are: Mystic Stew - Heal 3 damage. Magic Ointment - Trash a card in your play area or discard pile. Also draw a card. You may do these things in either order. Display Case - From the Dungeon Row, acquire a card, use a device, or defeat a monster (without paying Skill or Swords). Stolen Goods - Take an item from the Market Board (without paying additional Gold). 6"}, {"x": "lairs", "b": "Lairs & Lost Chambers Rulebook", "p": 7, "t": "Temple of Gold To place a cube on one of the pillars adjoining this lost chamber, you must be in a Wayshrine (the one on this tile, or any other Wayshrine in the dungeon). This cube placement requires you to make a \"donation\" of some amount of Gold from your personal supply (returning it to the Bank). You then receive the indicated reward. You may only donate to the Temple of Gold once. The four donations and their rewards are: - Heal 1 damage and take a Lockpick from the Bank. - Heal 2 damage. - Heal 1 damage and take a major secret at random from the Bank. - Heal 1 damage. You may also take an artifact from any room in the dungeon. (You may still only carry one artifact unless you have a Backpack.) If a donation provides you with more than one reward, you do not have to be able to take them all. For example: you could donate 2 Gold to take a Lockpick even if you have no damage to heal, or you could donate 8 Gold to heal damage even if you are unable to take an artifact. Umbrok Vessna's Hoard When you enter this lost chamber, take 5 Gold from the Bank and make +2 Clank! (You stealing from the hoard has caught the attention of the dragon.) When you either take the artifact or pick the chest in this lost chamber, you choose one of the other two rooms on this tile and immediately teleport there. No cubes are placed in this lost chamber. 7 rom the Bank. et at random artifact from nly carry one ne reward, you xample: you if you have no to heal damage 7"}, {"x": "lairs", "b": "Lairs & Lost Chambers Rulebook", "p": 8, "t": "Lairs In each lair, you will encounter a special kind of monster. When you ﬁ rst place a tile with a lair, place the corresponding monster marker (or markers) from the Bank in that lair. Lair of the Living Statues The three Living Statue markers are placed on the three marked spaces of this lair. While you're in the lair, you may ﬁ ght a Living Statue there. You must teleport after defeating a Living Statue (if there is another lair or lost chamber in the dungeon to teleport to). Lair of Medusa When you enter this lair, you must immediately either ﬁ ght Medusa or turn to stone (take 2 damage). You do not take additional damage if you remain in the lair, but you may choose to ﬁ ght on the same turn or a later one (even if you did not ﬁ ght Medusa when you ﬁ rst entered). Remember that you can't voluntarily take damage if you have no cubes in your supply, or if doing so would completely ﬁ ll your Health Meter. In these situations, you can't enter Medusa's Lair. While you have Medusa as a trophy, you ignore tunnel monsters (in addition to the point it gives you for the end of the game). Lair of the Sphinx While you're in this Lair, you have two different ways to defeat the Sphinx: use 4 Swords to ﬁ ght it, or pay 7 Skill to solve its riddle."}, {"x": "party", "b": "Adventuring Party Rulebook", "p": 1, "t": "The thieves' guild is recruiting! CLANK! Adventuring Party expands your merry band to include up to six players in your dungeon run! Want a new thieving identity? Shufﬂ e up as one of six unique characters, each with their own starting deck and special abilities! But beware: the ravenous hydra Hexavultus won't give up his treasures easily… Components 127 Cards 35 Dungeon Deck cards Two regular 10-card starting decks Six 10-card Character starting decks 12 Reserve cards 4 Mercenary, 4 Explore, 4 Secret Tome Six Player Pawns Six Character Boards 60 Clank! Cubes 30 in two new player colors Side Board 18 Minor Secrets 5 Artifacts 1 Backpack, 1 Crown, 1 Master Key 3 Invisibility Cloaks 2 Mastery Tokens Market Board Gold Boss Marker Character Tokens 4 Conscription, 1 Carnage, 10 Mana, 7 Cogwheel, 3 Behavior"}, {"x": "party", "b": "Adventuring Party Rulebook", "p": 2, "t": "Setup With CLANK! Adventuring Party, 5 or 6 players can now embark on a deck-building adventure on your existing game board. This includes any of the expansion game boards for CLANK! A Deck-Building Adventure. (Though you should not mix this with CLANK! Legacy: Acquisitions Incorporated until after you've completed the campaign. The paperwork is a nightmare.) The steps of setting up the original game are modiﬁ ed as follows. Note that where new components are added, unless otherwise speciﬁ ed, it is recommended that you remove those components when playing with 4 or fewer players. (This is because some components are intentionally limited.) A CLANK! Adventuring Party offers 30 Clank! cubes in two new player colors, and new pawns for both these colors and the four pre-existing colors. This expansion contains two 10-card decks that are identical to the four in the original game (6 Burgles, 2 Stumbles, 1 Sidestep, and 1 Scramble). A ﬁ fth and sixth player should take one of these if you wish for all players to begin with an identical deck. You may instead have each player choose one of the six characters in this expansion (even if you have 4 or fewer players). Each player takes the character board, custom starting deck, and any associated components for that character. These are detailed later, in the Characters section. B Add the ﬁ ve artifacts from this expansion to the original seven. If there are 5 players, shufﬂ e all artifacts face down, then select two at random to exclude from the game (returning them to the box). Place all artifacts in their spaces on the board (10 artifacts for 5 players, 12 for 6 players.) Artifacts with identical point values are stacked in the same space, with the original gold version on top and the new silver version on the bottom. Note that some expansions include artifacts with different point values (for example: the 33-point artifact in CLANK! Expeditions: Temple of the Ape Lords). If there is no space on the board for one of the new silver artifacts, place it on the artifact space with the closest value, putting the highervalued token on top. C There are no changes to the original setup of major secrets. D Add the new minor secret tokens to those from the original game. Shufﬂ e them all and place them face down in the Bank. (Do not place any on the board.) The new minor secrets have a differently colored background to help you separate them for a game in which you do not need them. E Place the Market Board beside the game board. This becomes your Market area. Add the new Backpack, Crown, and Master Key tokens to the originals, placing them all on the Market Board. Also place the Invisibility Cloak tokens on the Market board. (You may use these even if you have 4 or fewer players, though you should use only two Cloaks and not all three.) F There are no changes to the original setup of monkey idols. G Add new Mastery tokens as needed for the ﬁ fth and sixth player. H Add the new Gold tokens to your existing tokens to increase the size of your Bank. (You may do this even if you have 4 or fewer players; Gold is not limited.) I Place the new side board (with the new Rage Track and the Health Meters for the ﬁ fth and sixth player) up against the bottom edge of the game board. Place the Dragon marker on the ﬁ rst space of the side board's Rage Track. (For added ambience, you may replace the original Dragon marker with the new Hexavultus boss marker.) 2"}, {"x": "party", "b": "Adventuring Party Rulebook", "p": 3, "t": "3 J There are no changes to the original setup of the dragon cubes in the Dragon Bag. K Add the 4 additional copies of Mercenary, Explore, and Secret Tome cards to those from the original game. L Shufﬂ e the 35 new Dungeon Deck cards into the Dungeon Deck. (You may use these cards even if you have 4 or fewer players, although they are designed with more players in mind.) M Each player places their pawn outside the dungeon, shufﬂ es their starting deck, and draws a ﬁ ve-card hand as usual. N There are no changes to the amount of Clank! that the ﬁ rst through fourth players put in the Clank! area. Like the fourth player, the ﬁ fth and sixth players put no Clank! there. However, the ﬁ fth player takes 1 Gold from the Bank, and the sixth player takes 2 Gold. Party of Five (or Six!) Whether you are using the new characters in your game or not, these new rules will apply to your 5- and 6-player games. Taking an Artifact Many rooms now contain two artifacts, allowing two different players the opportunity to claim one. The ﬁ rst player to do so should take the original gold version. The second player to do so should take the new silver version. When totaling points at the end of the game, in the case of a tie between players who both have artifacts of the same value, the gold artifact (the one claimed ﬁ rst) wins the tie. Minor Secrets Minor secrets are now placed in the Bank during Setup, instead of on the board. When you enter a minor secret space during your turn, take one minor secret at random from the Bank and reveal it. You may only take one minor secret per room per turn. (You must re-enter a space on a later turn to take another minor secret.) It is possible (though uncommon) to run out of minor secrets during the game; in these cases, you get nothing when entering a minor secret space. Potion of Stealth This new minor secret is used during your turn to give you -1 Clank! and also give each of your opponents +1 Clank! You may use it even if you have no Clank! to remove. (Keep it until you use it, then return it to the box.) Market Items Backpack Although the backpack still allows you to carry an additional artifact, you can never pick up two artifacts from the same room. Invisibility Cloak This new item allows you to ignore monsters in tunnels when you move. (Also worth 5 points at the end of the game.)"}, {"x": "party", "b": "Adventuring Party Rulebook", "p": 4, "t": "In the Cards You'll ﬁ nd these new terms on cards in this expansion. React Many new cards in the expansion have text marked with the word React. It's a way to jump in during an opponent's turn and effectively expand your hand size when your next turn comes. If the condition described in a React occurs, you may announce this and play the card from your hand to your play area. Immediately draw a new card from your deck to replace the card from your hand. You do not use any of the resources or text on a card at the time you play it as a React. Instead, it remains in your play area until your next turn comes. On that turn, it joins all the other cards you'll now play: you get its resources and carry out its text just as though you'd played it normally. Example: While reﬁ lling the Dungeon Row at the end of an opponent's turn, a monster arrives in the row. You React with your Assassin, immediately drawing a card. You do not get the 2 Swords or the -2 Clank! until your next turn. If a React condition occurs early in an opponent's turn, you can still React later in their turn; you don't have to do it immediately when the condition is met. If you React and draw a card, that card might also let you React (to the same condition or to a different one). You can't use React to draw an additional card during your own turn - you must React during an opponent's turn (or, in the case of some cards, between turns, when reﬁ lling the Dungeon Row). When you play a card with React on your own turn, you still get everything else it shows - you just don't draw the extra card. Reacts make it especially important to remember that your hand should not be empty between turns; always end each of your turns by drawing your hand of cards for your next turn. (Your turn is then over, and you then reﬁ ll the Dungeon Row.) Arrive Choice Some new cards with Arrive text present all players with a choice. Each player chooses whether to do what the card offers, starting with the player about to begin their turn (or, in cases where a card Arrives in the middle of a turn, with the player taking their turn). If an Arrive Choice card presents two different options, each player must choose one of them. Example: When Leprechaun arrives in the Dungeon Row, players must choose one: either take 2 Gold and make 1 Clank!, or take 5 gold and make 3 Clank! 4 The cards from this expansion can be identiﬁ ed by this watermark in the game text box. You may use the watermarks to sort and remove cards when you wish to play without this expansion (or to remove them while you play, as they're revealed from the Dungeon Deck)."}, {"x": "party", "b": "Adventuring Party Rulebook", "p": 5, "t": "5 Characters CLANK! Adventuring Party includes six unique characters you can use in your game (even if you have 4 or fewer players). The characters in this expansion are made to be played against one another. You should not play them against regular starting decks. If you wish, you may mix these characters with any of the characters in the CLANK! Legacy: Acquisitions Incorporated expansions - the Upper Management Pack or The \"C\" Team Pack. During Setup, take the character board for your chosen character and place it in front of you, along with any special tokens you'll need (as described in the section detailing your character). Replace the regular 10-card starting deck with the 10-card starting deck for your character (which includes three unique cards). You can identify the cards in a character's deck by the icon along the right edge. Commanding the Mountain King's forces is Agnet, a toughas-nails military leader. Her voice and the king's are as one, and so is their thirst to take back everything they've lost to Nictotraxian and Hexavultus. During Setup, take the four conscription tokens and put them on your character board. Whenever you acquire a companion card, you may spend one of your conscription tokens (returning it to the box) to put the card on top of your deck instead of in your discard pile as usual. One card in your deck, Inspire, allows you to put one companion card on top of your deck when you end your turn, rather than discarding it along with all your other cards. Agnet begins the game with a companion, Rebel Squire, in her deck. She also has Defensive Position, a card that gives her Swords while in a Crystal Cave. Agnet's starting deck contains 5 Burgles, 2 Stumbles, 1 Defensive Position, 1 Inspire, and 1 Rebel Squire. Plundering riches is fun for the elf adventurer D'allan, but he's not in it just for personal gain. He wants his rarest ﬁ nds displayed in a museum for everyone to enjoy. No additional tokens are needed to play D'allan. During the game, place the ﬁ rst dragon egg you acquire in the designated space on your character board. Do the same with your ﬁ rst artifact, crown, and monkey idol. These four tokens are your \"Finds,\" and three cards in your deck give you bonuses for having them - Collection gives you Gold, while Competition and Exhibit give one special reward (depending on the Find): Dragon Egg - -2 Clank! Monkey Idol - Trash a Burgle from your play area or discard pile. Crown - You don't have to stop in Crystal Caves this turn. Artifact - You may buy from the market this turn. (Any number of items, at regular cost.) Example: You have a dragon egg and an artifact, both placed on your character board. When you play Exhibit, you may choose either -2 Clank! or to buy from the market this turn. If other players discover your Finds before you, not to worry - three of D'allan's cards React to that situation. D'allan's starting deck contains 5 Burgles, 2 Stumbles, 1 Collection, 1 Competition, and 1 Exhibit."}, {"x": "party", "b": "Adventuring Party Rulebook", "p": 6, "t": "6 Although the brutal orc Garignar was once a minion of Hexavultus, he has seen the error of his ways. Now he's returning to the dungeon he once patrolled - not to ﬁ ght adventurers, but to steal from the hydra! During Setup, take the carnage token and place it on the top space (\"Start\") of your character board. The ﬁ rst time you defeat a Monster card each turn (even the Goblin), advance the carnage token one space clockwise around the circle of rewards shown on your board and take the reward you move to. Fighting a monster in a tunnel when you move does not advance the carnage token. In most spaces, you must choose from one of two different rewards: 1 Gold or 1 Skill, 1 Skill or 1 Boot, 2 Gold or draw a card, and 2 Skill or heal one damage. The fourth space rewards you with a minor secret from the Bank. Garignar begins the game with Wallop, starting him with 2 Swords! Scavenge earns gold for defeating monsters in tunnels, while Ransack can React when your opponents beat you to defeating monsters. Garignar's starting deck contains 5 Burgles, 2 Stumbles, 1 Ransack, 1 Scavenge, and 1 Wallop. Larceny is so much easier when you use magic! The talented mage Lenara has decided to use her abilities for thievery and proﬁ t. During Setup, place the 10 mana tokens next to your character board in a pool. Two cards in your deck, Channel and Study, give you mana to spend (with bonus mana for secrets, potions, and Secret Tomes). When you receive mana, place it on your character board. Take care to keep separate the mana you've earned from the mana you haven't! At any time during your turn, you may spend your available mana to cast three different spells. Each spell may be cast only once per turn. Transﬁ gure costs 3 mana, and lets you discard a card, then draw a card. Duplicate costs 5 mana, and creates a virtual copy of any card in your play area (all its resources and text). Levitate costs 7 mana, and lets you immediately acquire a card without paying its regular skill cost. You put it in your hand, meaning you will play it this turn. Remove any mana you spend from your character board and return it to the pool of mana tokens you can earn. You are limited to the 10 mana tokens provided; you can't save any more on your character board. Most characters begin the game with 2 Boots in their deck, but one of Lenara's is replaced with Mystic Slide, allowing her to teleport! Lenara's starting deck contains 5 Burgles, 2 Stumbles, 1 Channel, 1 Mystic Slide, and 1 Study."}, {"x": "party", "b": "Adventuring Party Rulebook", "p": 7, "t": "7 He's a cat. You could ask him how he's also a professional thief, but do you really expect an answer? During Setup, take the three behavior tokens and place them face up on your character board in the spaces with the corresponding icons: 1 Skill in the Play space, 1 Sword in the Hiss space, and 1 Boot in the Chase space. Two cards in your deck, Cattitude and Saunter, tell you to ﬂ ip a behavior token face down. You must choose one that is face up. You gain its resource to use during that turn. When you end your turn (before reﬁ lling the Dungeon Row), if all three behavior tokens are face down, you cause a Dragon Attack! (It is not optional.) Draw exactly four cubes, ignoring the Dragon Marker's current space on the Rage Track (and any additional Danger from the Dungeon Row or Countdown Track). You take no damage from any cubes of your color that are pulled. Instead, return those cubes to your supply. (Other cubes are treated normally.) Once the attack is resolved, draw your hand for your next turn, then ﬂ ip all three of your behavior tokens face up, making them available again for future turns. (Finally, reﬁ ll the Dungeon Row normally for the end of your turn, if necessary. This may cause an additional, normal Dragon Attack.) Saunter doubles the reward from the behavior token you ﬂ ip, once you have an artifact. There's also another sneaky trick: Pussyfoot lets you ignore monsters in tunnels. Whiskers' starting deck contains 5 Burgles, 2 Stumbles, 1 Cattitude, 1 Pussyfoot, and 1 Saunter. Undying since the time of the Ape Lords, MonkeyBot Prime is the greatest not-quite-living monument to their civilization. It scoops up any treasure it ﬁ nds, with little regard to the noise it makes. During Setup, take the seven cogwheel tokens and place them on the seven spaces of your character board (covering the icons). Whenever you are damaged in a Dragon Attack, remove the leftmost cogwheel token and return it to the box. Remove only one cogwheel token per attack, no matter how much damage you take. Do not remove tokens if you take damage by some other means (such as moving through a tunnel with a Monster icon). Do not replace any cogwheel tokens when you heal damage. As you remove cogwheel tokens, you reveal the rewards shown beneath. During each of your turns, you get all of the rewards you've revealed: Skill, Swords, and Boots. The MonkeyBot Prime is noisy, with two cards - Bolt and Persist - that make Clank! However, Persist also heals you, while Bolt doesn't kick in until you've picked up an artifact (and it then also gives you extra gold). Be sure to grab a monkey idol for a quick escape, because once you have one, Primacy lets you run through Crystal Caves without stopping. MonkeyBot Prime's starting deck contains 5 Burgles, 2 Stumbles, 1 Bolt, 1 Persist, and 1 Primacy."}, {"x": "party", "b": "Adventuring Party Rulebook", "p": 8, "t": "www.direwolfdigital.com /direwolfdigital @direwolfdigital Credits Game Design Evan Lorentz Design Direction Paul Dennen Executive Producer Scott Martins Character Design and Illustration Raul Ramos Art and Graphic Design Anika Burrell, Derek Herring, Nate Storm, Alain Viesca Card Illustration Justine De Leon, Harvey Heinrich, Rastislav Le, Samson Ledesma, Paul Roberts Medalla, Lorene Angel Mocorro, Melvin Quito, Raul Ramos Production Evan Lorentz Additional Game Design and Game Development Tim McKnight, Yuri Tolpin Special thanks to: All of the awesome Dire Wolf Digital team members, and their friends and families, who helped to playtest CLANK! 8 Published by: Dire Wolf Digital. © 2020 Dire Wolf Digital, Inc. All rights reserved. Dire Wolf and the Dire Wolf logo are registered trademarks of Dire Wolf Digital, Inc."}];
